WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.130 --> 00:00:02.500
- The scientific discussion of X three.

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:06.840
So, this is detailed on the website,

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:09.850
where we make multiple references

00:00:09.850 --> 00:00:11.364
and the reason in scientific papers

00:00:11.364 --> 00:00:14.010
that multiple references are made

00:00:14.010 --> 00:00:15.200
and sometimes you scroll to the bottom

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.620
of a scientific paper

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:18.421
and you see hundreds of references,

00:00:18.421 --> 00:00:22.560
it's because all these things interrelate.

00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:26.080
So when somebody looks at one
of the observations we've made

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:27.310
or one of the references,

00:00:27.310 --> 00:00:29.640
and pulls a sentence out of one study

00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:31.659
and says, well, X3 is not this,

00:00:31.659 --> 00:00:34.340
well, right, that's why we
referenced multiple studies,

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:36.493
so these things all relate together.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:42.600
Let me go back and talk about the history.

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:47.210
So I had been observing as
a bone density researcher

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:50.640
and I developed some machines,

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:53.253
some devices that stimulate bone density.

00:00:54.481 --> 00:00:57.500
What I was doing was
loading the human body

00:00:57.500 --> 00:00:59.320
at optimized ranges of motion,

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:01.940
so where humans naturally
absorb high impact.

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:03.528
So in the upper body about right here

00:01:03.528 --> 00:01:08.200
where there's 120 degree
angle of inclusion right here,

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:10.495
delivering force here, same mathematics,

00:01:10.495 --> 00:01:13.020
same geometry in other joints of the body.

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:15.519
And seeing very aggressive
bone growth as a result

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:17.570
of loading those positions.

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:22.370
I was made aware of what was
going on at Westside Barbell

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:24.043
which is a small gym in Ohio

00:01:24.043 --> 00:01:27.410
that had broken more
than 140 world records

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:29.570
using variable resistance.

00:01:29.570 --> 00:01:34.233
And I thought, okay, so they're
doing loading at the bottom

00:01:34.233 --> 00:01:37.570
and then doing kind of a
hyper loading at the top

00:01:37.570 --> 00:01:39.340
by using bands with weights.

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:40.610
And I thought that's very interesting.

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:43.515
It's a similar line of logic
to what I'm working on.

00:01:43.515 --> 00:01:48.515
Then, in 2008, Professor
Anderson and researchers

00:01:48.916 --> 00:01:52.840
published a study that
was a look at the results

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:56.570
that were taken from a
group of individuals.

00:01:56.570 --> 00:01:59.170
So they took the Cornell athletes

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:01.650
from all sorts of different
sports, it was a big study,

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:05.330
and half of them did their
regular training protocol.

00:02:05.330 --> 00:02:08.410
The other half did the
variable resistance protocols.

00:02:08.410 --> 00:02:10.513
So they used actually
lower amount of weight

00:02:10.513 --> 00:02:12.560
than they would normally lift.

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:14.360
And then they added bands,

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:16.050
so it was hyper loading at the top,

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:18.660
more than they could handle
at the bottom normally,

00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:21.090
and then a lower load at the bottom.

00:02:21.090 --> 00:02:22.606
This is really important to point out

00:02:22.606 --> 00:02:24.958
that there was a curb to this loading.

00:02:24.958 --> 00:02:27.684
They may have been
handling X at the bottom

00:02:27.684 --> 00:02:32.684
and 1.3X at the top, but the
point is they use the variance.

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:38.130
Now, the results in that study
showed two to three times

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:41.089
the amount of strength
gained in the period of time,

00:02:41.089 --> 00:02:45.750
it was 24 weeks, versus
the control, very profound.

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:49.479
Now, this was a verification
of what Westside Barbell

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:52.380
had been doing, and fantastic.

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:54.643
And there's observations
that have been made

00:02:54.643 --> 00:02:57.060
with chains and bands
and all kinds of ways

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:59.170
to vary the resistance.

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:02.140
But then I took my medical device,

00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:06.208
and there was a study done in
London, a hospital in London.

00:03:06.208 --> 00:03:08.940
And we were looking at
post-menopausal females.

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:10.157
So these are not athletes,

00:03:10.157 --> 00:03:13.106
these are actually de-conditioned,
post-menopausal females.

00:03:13.106 --> 00:03:17.342
And something really amazing
was brought to light,

00:03:17.342 --> 00:03:20.130
which was we were loading these women

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:24.410
with seven, eight, nine
times their body weight

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:25.860
through their hip.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.140
So take your body weight
and multiply it by eight.

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:31.143
Incredible force.

00:03:32.352 --> 00:03:35.290
Professional weightlifters
don't use that kind of weight

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:37.550
and these were de-conditioned women.

00:03:37.550 --> 00:03:42.451
Now they built up to that over
a six month period of time.

00:03:42.451 --> 00:03:45.620
But it was amazing what
they were capable of.

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:48.040
And that was the whole
objective behind compression

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:49.493
of bone and bone growth.

00:03:50.741 --> 00:03:52.941
And that's what also
happens in high impact.

00:03:54.770 --> 00:03:56.057
I came home back to the States

00:03:56.057 --> 00:03:59.850
and I looked at the level of
loading that they were using,

00:03:59.850 --> 00:04:03.113
and then looked at the level of loading

00:04:03.113 --> 00:04:05.470
that the American College
of Sports Medicine

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:07.483
has in most of their documentation.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:11.330
The levels of loading that non-athletic

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:13.700
versus athletic people deal with,

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:15.072
with their lower extremities.

00:04:15.072 --> 00:04:20.072
And it was 1.3 to 1.53
multiples of body weight.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:25.160
So this tells us that there's
a sevenfold difference

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:27.330
just based on those two datasets.

00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:30.340
Now populations, athletes,
we're not looking at that.

00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:33.027
But ultimately,

00:04:33.027 --> 00:04:36.630
1.3 to 1.53 versus,

00:04:36.630 --> 00:04:39.010
let's say on average 8.5,

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:41.500
I think it ended up being
8.7 multiples body weight.

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:44.980
That's a sevenfold difference.

00:04:44.980 --> 00:04:47.810
So that made me look at the Anderson study

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:49.293
and say all right, well,

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:54.560
this whole idea of X here and 1.3X here

00:04:54.560 --> 00:04:57.497
is barely scratching the surface

00:04:57.497 --> 00:05:01.510
of what we may actually be capable of

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:03.570
with stimulating muscular growth.

00:05:03.570 --> 00:05:05.870
What we really need is a lower weight here

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:07.630
where our joints are compromised,

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:09.311
and a far higher weight here.

00:05:09.311 --> 00:05:12.117
Not only can we go higher in repetitions,

00:05:12.117 --> 00:05:15.380
we can fatigue multiple ranges of motion,

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:19.040
something you cannot do
with a static weight.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.500
So you go to fatigue
here with a high weight,

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:23.570
then when you can't hit
that, then you go to fatigue

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:24.900
at a medium weight.

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:27.820
Then at the end of your set
where you can barely move,

00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:30.604
you go to fatigue here and
really short repetitions

00:05:30.604 --> 00:05:33.112
with an even lower weight,
really easy on the joints,

00:05:33.112 --> 00:05:38.112
and the amount of fatigue
that goes through the muscle

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:42.510
is far beyond what you would get

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:44.760
with any sort of static weight system.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.710
Also, the amount of force,

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:49.950
and this is a question that we get.

00:05:49.950 --> 00:05:52.360
It's just bands or I don't understand,

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:56.130
I can get a band for $40 at Walmart,

00:05:56.130 --> 00:06:00.090
I want you to look at
this block of solid latex.

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:02.020
This is one of the heavier bands.

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:04.234
That's how much weight you're moving,

00:06:04.234 --> 00:06:07.560
that would add for a six foot tall person

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:12.560
that ends up being about a 250
pound chest press, at peak.

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:15.070
You're gonna fatigue there
for a few repetitions,

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:18.580
which normally people don't
handle very many repetitions,

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.808
the average person, handle
very many repetitions

00:06:20.808 --> 00:06:22.090
at 250 pounds.

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:24.770
And then you diminish the range.

00:06:24.770 --> 00:06:28.329
So all these things, all
these studies interrelate

00:06:28.329 --> 00:06:32.280
to make the rationale behind X3.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:33.563
One clarification.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:36.842
So the study that was done in London

00:06:36.842 --> 00:06:39.145
where we exposed the very high loads

00:06:39.145 --> 00:06:43.520
to the lower body and the kinetic chain,

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:46.104
these women weren't squatting

00:06:46.104 --> 00:06:48.470
seven, eight, nine
times their body weight.

00:06:48.470 --> 00:06:52.330
The load was just exposed in
the impact ready position.

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:55.961
So like I said, 120 degree
angle of inclusion right there,

00:06:55.961 --> 00:06:57.730
that's, when you trip and fall,

00:06:57.730 --> 00:06:59.610
that's how you absorb the force.

00:06:59.610 --> 00:07:03.140
So these were bone compressive movements

00:07:03.140 --> 00:07:04.770
in the optimized range of motion,

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:06.590
the impact range of motion.

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:09.655
So this was to stimulate
bone density growth.

00:07:09.655 --> 00:07:14.655
But the clarity that it gave me

00:07:14.730 --> 00:07:18.485
to develop X3 was that
we are really missing out

00:07:18.485 --> 00:07:20.760
on so many triggers for growth

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:24.938
by not looking at the massive difference

00:07:24.938 --> 00:07:28.590
between our capability in the strong range

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:30.740
and the capability in the weak range.

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:33.952
And ultimately, if you
look at human movement,

00:07:33.952 --> 00:07:38.600
if you look at sprinters, they
have 180 degrees available

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:41.800
in their knee joint, but
they only use seven degrees

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:44.370
when they fire off their
toe to move forward.

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:45.330
So why is that?

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:46.593
That's the optimized range of motion.

00:07:46.593 --> 00:07:50.120
We use the optimized range
of motion all the time

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:55.040
to absorb or produce
great amount of forces,

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:57.668
far heavier than we could ever lift.

00:07:57.668 --> 00:08:00.180
Now, if we use variable resistance,

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:05.084
if we doubled down on the
variants of resistance,

00:08:05.084 --> 00:08:10.084
and maybe for some,
forget about the weights,

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:12.843
we have growth potential
that we've never tapped.

